{"title_page": "Jurangmangu railway station", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Jurangmangu Station\n| native_name      = <small>''Stasiun Jurangmangu''</small>\n| image            = {{#property:p18}}\n| image_size       = \n| image_caption    = Jurangmangu Station, Photo was taken on {{startdate|2019|03|12|df=y}}\n| address          = Jalan Akses Jurangmangu, [[Ciputat]], [[South Tangerang]] 15413\n| country          = [[Indonesia]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|-6.288612|106.729154|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation        = +25 M\n| line             = {{rint|jakarta|green}} [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang\u2013Rangkasbitung|Green Line]]\n| other            =\n| platform         = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks           = 2\n| parking          = Available\n| bicycle          =\n| baggage_check    =\n| passengers       =\n| pass_year        =\n| pass_percent     =\n| pass_system      =\n| opened           = {{startdate|2009|09|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan\">{{cite news|url=https://akumassa.org/id/stasiun-jurang-mangu-stasiun-anyar-di-kota-tangerang-selatan/|title=Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan|language=id|access-date=8 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tangerangnews.com/tangsel/read/1315/Stasiun-Jurang-Mangu-Resmi-Dioperasikan|title=Stasiun Jurangmangu Resmi Dioperasikan|language=id|access-date=16 December 2009}}</ref>\n| rebuilt          = 2002<ref name=\"Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan\"/>\n| ADA              = Available\n| code             = JMG\n| owned            = [[Indonesian Railway Company]]\n| operator         = [[Kereta Commuter Indonesia]]\n| zone             =\n| services         = {{s-rail|title=KRL Jabodetabek}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Serpong-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|rows2=4}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Parung Panjang-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|hide2=true}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Maja-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|hide2=true}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Rangkasbitung-Tanah Abang|next=Sudimara|previous=Pondok Ranji|hide2=true}}\n| map_type         = Indonesia Jakarta\n| mpassengers      = \n| map_caption      = Location in Southern Jakarta\n| borough          = [[Banten]]\n}}\n\n'''Jurangmangu Station''' ('''JMG''') is a railway station on the [[KAI Commuter Jabodetabek|KA Commuter Jabodetabek]] [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang-Maja|Green Line]] in [[Ciputat]], [[South Tangerang]].\n\nThe station is located at the elevation of 25 metres above sea level. Jurangmangu is one of two stations serving the Bintaro housing area, along with [[Pondok Ranji railway station|Pondok Ranji]], located about 2 kilometers northeast. It is also located near the Bintaro XChange mall.\n\n==Trains and services==\nThe lines below are the lines that stop and serve in the Jurangmangu station\n* {{rint|jakarta|green}} [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang\u2013Rangkasbitung|Green Line]]: from [[Tanah Abang railway station|Tanah Abang]] to [[Rangkasbitung railway station|Rangkasbitung]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Train Stations in Indonesia|Banten}}\n{{KA Commuter Jabodetabek stations}}\n\n[[Category:South Tangerang]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Banten]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2009]]\n\n{{Indonesia-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name             = Jurangmangu Station\n| native_name      = <small>''Stasiun Jurangmangu''</small>\n| image            = {{#property:p18}}\n| image_size       = \n| image_caption    = Jurangmangu Station, Photo was taken on {{startdate|2019|03|12|df=y}}\n| address          = Jalan Akses Jurangmangu, [[Ciputat]], [[South Tangerang]] 15413\n| country          = [[Indonesia]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|-6.288612|106.729154|display=inline,title}}\n| elevation        = +25 M\n| line             = {{rint|jakarta|green}} [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang\u2013Rangkasbitung|Green Line]]\n| other            =\n| platform         = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks           = 2\n| parking          = Available\n| bicycle          =\n| baggage_check    =\n| passengers       =\n| pass_year        =\n| pass_percent     =\n| pass_system      =\n| opened           = {{startdate|2009|09|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan\">{{cite news|url=https://akumassa.org/id/stasiun-jurang-mangu-stasiun-anyar-di-kota-tangerang-selatan/|title=Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan|language=id|access-date=8 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tangerangnews.com/tangsel/read/1315/Stasiun-Jurang-Mangu-Resmi-Dioperasikan|title=Stasiun Jurangmangu Resmi Dioperasikan|language=id|access-date=16 December 2009}}</ref>\n| rebuilt          = 2002<ref name=\"Stasiun Jurangmangu, Stasiun Anyar di Kota Tangerang Selatan\"/>\n| ADA              = Available\n| code             = JMG\n| owned            = [[Indonesian Railway Company]]\n| operator         = [[Kereta Commuter Indonesia]]\n| zone             =\n| services         = {{s-rail|title=KRL Jabodetabek}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Serpong-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|rows2=4}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Parung Panjang-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|hide2=true}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Maja-Tanah Abang|previous=Pondok Ranji|next=Sudimara|hide2=true}}\n{{s-line|system=KRL Jabodetabek|line=Rangkasbitung-Tanah Abang|next=Sudimara|previous=Pondok Ranji|hide2=true}}\n| map_type         = Indonesia Jakarta\n| mpassengers      = \n| map_caption      = Location in Southern Jakarta\n| borough          = [[Banten]]\n}}\n\n'''Jurangmangu Station''' ('''JMG''') is a railway station on the [[KAI Commuter Jabodetabek|KA Commuter Jabodetabek]] [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang-Maja|Green Line]] in [[Ciputat]], [[South Tangerang]].\n\nThe station is located at the elevation of 25 metres above sea level. Jurangmangu is one of two stations serving the Bintaro housing area, along with [[Pondok Ranji railway station|Pondok Ranji]], located about 2 kilometers northeast. It is also located near the Bintaro XChange mall.\n\n==Trains and services==\nThe lines below are the lines that stop and serve in the Jurangmangu station\n* {{rint|jakarta|green}} [[KA Commuter Line Tanah Abang\u2013Rangkasbitung|Green Line]]: from [[Tanah Abang railway station|Tanah Abang]] to [[Rangkasbitung railway station|Rangkasbitung]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Train Stations in Indonesia|Banten}}\n{{KA Commuter Jabodetabek stations}}\n\n[[Category:South Tangerang]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Banten]]\n[[Category:Transport in Banten]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2009]]\n\n{{Indonesia-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "OktaRama2010", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:Transport in BantenusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jurangmangu_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Grand Rapids Rampage", "text_new": "{{short description|Arena football team}}\n{{Infobox indoor American football team\n| name = Grand Rapids Rampage\n| logo =\n| helmet = Grand Rapids Rampage Helmet Logo 2007-2008.png\n| founded = 1998\n| folded = 2009\n| city = [[Van Andel Arena]]<br> in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan]]\n| misc =\n| uniform = Image:AFL-Uniform-Current-GRD.PNG\n| colors = Red, black, silver, white<br>{{Color box|#d33}} {{Color box|#000}} {{Color box|silver}} {{Color box|white}}\n| coach = [[Steve Thonn]]\n| owner = Arena Football League\n| mascot = Blitz\n| league = \n[[Arena Football League]] ({{AFL Year|1998}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2009}})\n*American Conference (1998\u20132009)\n**[[Central Division (AFL)|Central]] (1998\u20132009)\n| team_history =\n*Grand Rapids Rampage (1998\u20132009)\n| no_conf_champs      = 0\n| conf_champs         = \n<small>Prior to 2005, the AFL did not have conference championship games</small>\n| no_div_champs       = 1\n| div_champs          = \n*'''Central:''' {{AFL Year|2001}}\n| no_league_champs    = 1\n| league_champs       =\n*[[ArenaBowl XV|2001]]\n| playoff_appearances =\n*{{AFL Year|1999}}, {{AFL Year|2000}}, {{AFL Year|2001}}, {{AFL Year|2002}}, {{AFL Year|2003}}, {{AFL Year|2009}}\n| no_playoff_appearances = 6\n| arena_years         = \n*[[Van Andel Arena]] (1998\u20132009)\n}}\n\nThe '''Grand Rapids Rampage''' were an [[arena football]] team based in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]. The team began play in 1998 in the [[Arena Football League]] as an expansion team. They were last coached by [[Steve Thonn]]. Their home arena was the [[Van Andel Arena]].\n\n==History==\nThe team became the [[Detroit Drive]] in 1988 and, in 1994, became the [[Massachusetts Marauders]] for one season. Three years later, DP Fox Ventures, L.L.C. bought the team and moved it to Grand Rapids.\n\nThe team under its final name dates back to 1997. They began play as a professional team in 1998 in Grand Rapids, Michigan, when [[Dan DeVos]] purchased the [[Massachusetts Marauders|Detroit Drive/Massachusetts Marauders]] franchise out of bankruptcy court. Grand Rapids was the smallest market in which the AFL had a franchise at the times of its disbanding. The Rampage played in the Van Andel Arena, which is also the home of the [[American Hockey League|AHL]]'s [[Grand Rapids Griffins]]. They competed in the Central Division of the American Conference.\n\nThe Grand Rapids Rampage started play in 1998 under coach [[Michael Trigg]]. In 2001, with notable players [[Clint Dolezel]], and [[Terrill Shaw]], the Rampage went on to win their first [[ArenaBowl XV|ArenaBowl]]. This game was broadcast live on the [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Network]].\n\nThe Rampage's official mascot was a [[Rhinoceros]] named '''Blitz'''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |title=http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |access-date=2006-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050110073220/http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |archive-date=2005-01-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Rampage had a rivalry with the [[Nashville Kats]], one which dates back to the original Kats. This rivalry solidified with the Rampage's defeat of Nashville in ArenaBowl XV.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/rampage-down-kats-in-arenabowl/n-2707556 |title=Rampage down Kats in Arenabowl |date=August 19, 2001 |publisher=OurSports Central |work=oursportscentral.com |accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Rampage also shared a rivalry with the [[Chicago Rush]], known as the Amtrak Classic, after the [[Amtrak]] railway system which connects the two cities. On July 6, 2008, the Amtrak Classic added an interesting chapter as the Rampage, losers of their last six meetings with Chicago, defeated their heavily favored opponents on the road. Grand Rapids entered the game as a 6 seed, and upended the #1 seeded Rush 58-41, in a game of controversial penalties and brawls.\n\nOn March 5, 2010, it was announced that the Rampage were officially out of business and had no plans to return.<ref>http://www.mlive.com/rampage/index.ssf/2010/03/rampage_dead_as_arena_football.html</ref>\n\n==Logo==\nThe Rampage's logo was a red [[rhinoceros]]. Its end zone is unique as being the only end zone that does not feature a team name or city. It simply says Arena Football in red with a black background.\n\n==Rampage highlights==\n* On Sunday, June 23, 2002, the Rampage hosted a game against the [[Georgia Force]]. After a low-scoring first quarter, the Rampage took a 28-15 halftime lead. However, the Force refused to go down, as they had a 41-35 lead with only 12 seconds left in the game. On one play, Quarterback Clint Dolezel threw a game-winning 31-yd touchdown pass to Offensive Specialist [[Steve Smith (wide receiver, born 1974)|Steve Smith]] (who hadn't played a down that game until the final play). The Rampage would win 42-41. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is ranked at #13.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29355&CLIP_FILE_ID=33336&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29355&CLIP_FILE_ID=33336&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* On Saturday, February 5, 2005, in a road game against their division-rival, the [[Colorado Crush]], Rampage quarterback [[Michael Bishop (football player)|Michael Bishop]] became the first Arena Football League player to run for 100 yards in a single game. It was only Bishop's third-ever start, yet he accomplished this feat on just six attempts. Despite falling 72-56, Bishop's helped set a bold new record. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is ranked at #12.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29664&CLIP_FILE_ID=33642&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29664&CLIP_FILE_ID=33642&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* In a pregame warm-up, quarterback Michael Bishop threw a pass from one end zone, across the field, through the uprights and into the stands. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is tied at #9.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=30570&CLIP_FILE_ID=34585&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=30570&CLIP_FILE_ID=34585&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* On Monday, March 24, 2008, The Rampage set the AFL record for the most points scored in a single game by a road team, beating the [[Kansas City Brigade]] 92-52. [[James MacPherson (American football)|James Macpherson]] went 24-27, nine touchdowns, and 307 yards in his first start for the Rampage. MacPherson would later go on to break the franchise record for touchdown passes in a later game.\n\n==Season-by-season==\n{{Main|List of Grand Rapids Rampage seasons}}\n\n==Notable players==\n\n===Arena Football Hall of Famers===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style= \"background: #d33; color: white\" align=\"center\"| '''Grand Rapids Rampage Hall of Famers'''\n|-\n!width=60px style=\"background: #000; color: white\" |No.\n!style=\"background: #000; color: white\" |Name\n!style=\"background: #000; color: white\" |Year inducted\n!style=\"background: #000; color: white\" |Position(s)\n!style=\"background: #000; color: white\" |Years w/ Rampage\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 13 || [[Clint Dolezel]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2012 || style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Quarterback|QB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2001-2003\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 84 || [[Fred Gayles]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2002 || style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Wide Receiver|WR]]/[[Defensive Back|DB]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1998\n|}\n\n===Individual awards===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#d33; color:white;\"| '''Kicker of the Year'''\n|-\n!  style=\"width:50px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Season   \n!  style=\"width:150px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Player\n!  style=\"width:100px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Position\n|-\n|{{AFL Year|2001}}||[[Brian Gowins]]||[[Placekicker|K]]\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#d33; color:white;\"| '''Most Inspirational Player of the Year'''\n|-\n!  style=\"width:50px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Season   \n!  style=\"width:150px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Player\n!  style=\"width:100px; background:#000; color:white;\"| Position\n|-\n|{{AFL Year|2001}}||[[JoJo Polk]]||[[Defensive Back|DB]]\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===All-Arena players===\nThe following Rampage players were named to [[All-Arena]] Teams:\n* '''QB''' [[Craig Kusick, Jr.]] (1), [[Clint Dolezel]] (1)\n* '''WR''' [[Kenny Higgins]] (1)\n* '''WR/DB''' [[Willis Marshall]] (1)\n* '''WR/LB''' [[Michael Baker (arena football)|Michael Baker]] (1)\n* '''K''' [[Brian Gowins]] (1)\n\n===All-Ironman players===\nThe following Rampage players were named to All-Ironman Teams:\n* '''FB/LB''' [[Chris Ryan (arena football)|Chris Ryan]] (1), [[Chris Avery]] (2)\n* '''WR/DB''' [[Timon Marshall]] (1), [[Jermaine Lewis (Arena football)|Jermaine Lewis]] (1)\n* '''WR/LB''' [[Michael Baker (arena football)|Michael Baker]] (1), [[Jerome Riley]] (1)\n* '''OL/DL''' [[Winfield Garnett]] (1)\n\n===All-Rookie players===\nThe following Rampage players were named to All-Rookie Teams:\n* '''OL/DL''' [[Buster Stanley]], [[Corey Mayfield]], [[Israel Raybon]]\n* '''LB''' [[Michael McFadden (arena football)|Michael McFadden]]\n* '''DB''' [[Chris Martin (arnea football)|Chris Martin]]\n* '''DS''' [[JoJo Polk]]\n* '''K''' [[Brian Gowins]], [[Peter Martinez]]\n\n==Venue location and front office==\nThe Grand Rapids Rampage played in the Van Andel Arena, which is located in downtown Grand Rapids.\n\n==Coaches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n![[Head coach]]\n!Tenure\n!Regular season<br>record (W\u2013L)\n!Postseason<br>record (W\u2013L)\n!Most recent coaching staff\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Michael Trigg]]\n|[[1998 Arena Football League season|1998]]\u2013[[2003 Arena Football League season|2003]]\n|43\u201341<ref name=\"AFO\">{{cite web |url=http://www.arenafan.com/history/?page=coaches&coach=37 |title=ArenaFan Online: AFL Coaches: Michael Trigg |accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\n|3\u20134<ref name=\"AFO\"/>\n|\n|AFL Coach of the year (2001).<ref name=\"AFO\"/><br>[[ArenaBowl XV]] winning head coach.<ref name=\"AFO\"/><br>Assistant coach: [[Will McClay]] (1998 - [[1999 Arena Football League season|1999]])<br>became head coach<br>of the [[Philadelphia Soul]] (2004).\n|-\n|[[Bob Cortese]]\n|[[2004 Arena Football League season|2004]]\n|1\u201310<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arenafan.com/history/?page=coaches&coach=51 |title=ArenaFan Online: AFL Coaches: Bob Cortese |accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\n|0\u20130\n|\n|Let go during the season\n|-\n|Rick Frazier\n|2004\n|0\u20135<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arenafan.com/history/?page=coaches&coach=43 |title=ArenaFan Online: AFL Coaches: Rick Frazier |accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\n|0\u20130\n|\n|Replaced Bob Cortese during the season.\n|-\n|[[Sparky McEwen]]\n|[[2005 Arena Football League season|2005]]\u2013[[2007 Grand Rapids Rampage season|2007]]\n|13\u201335<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arenafan.com/history/?page=coaches&coach=75 |title=ArenaFan Online: AFL Coaches: Sparky McEwen |accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref>\n|0\u20130\n|\n|Grand Rapids assistant coach ([[2001 Arena Football League season|2001]] - 2003).\n|-\n|[[Steve Thonn]]\n|[[2008 Grand Rapids Rampage season|2008]]\n|6\u201310\n|2\u20131\n|[[Defensive coordinator|DC]] / Director of Player Personnel:<br>Ron Selesky<br>Line coach: Darrin Kenney<br>[[Special Teams|ST]] Coordinator and [[Fullback (American football)|FB]] / [[Linebacker|LB]] coach:<br>Paul Reinke<br>Manager of Football Ops. / Assist. coach:<br>Rod Miller\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.arenafan.com/teams/?page=clubhouse&team=40 Grand Rapids Rampage at ArenaFan.com]\n\n{{Grand Rapids Rampage}}\n{{Grand Rapids, Michigan}}\n{{ArenaBowl XV}}\n{{Defunct Arena Football League franchises}}\n\n[[Category:Grand Rapids Rampage| ]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:2009 disestablishments in Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Arena football team}}\n{{Infobox indoor American football team\n| name = Grand Rapids Rampage\n| logo =\n| helmet = Grand Rapids Rampage Helmet Logo 2007-2008.png\n| founded = 1998\n| folded = 2009\n| city = [[Van Andel Arena]]<br> in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan]]\n| misc =\n| uniform = Image:AFL-Uniform-Current-GRD.PNG\n| colors = Red, black, silver, white<br>{{Color box|#d33}} {{Color box|#000}} {{Color box|silver}} {{Color box|white}}\n| coach = [[Steve Thonn]]\n| owner = Arena Football League\n| mascot = Blitz\n| league = \n[[Arena Football League]] ({{AFL Year|1998}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2009}})\n*American Conference (1998\u20132009)\n**[[Central Division (AFL)|Central]] (1998\u20132009)\n| team_history =\n*Grand Rapids Rampage (1998\u20132009)\n| no_conf_champs      = 0\n| conf_champs         = \n<small>Prior to 2005, the AFL did not have conference championship games</small>\n| no_div_champs       = 1\n| div_champs          = \n*'''Central:''' {{AFL Year|2001}}\n| no_league_champs    = 1\n| league_champs       =\n*[[ArenaBowl XV|2001]]\n| playoff_appearances =\n*{{AFL Year|1999}}, {{AFL Year|2000}}, {{AFL Year|2001}}, {{AFL Year|2002}}, {{AFL Year|2003}}, {{AFL Year|2009}}\n| no_playoff_appearances = 6\n| arena_years         = \n*[[Van Andel Arena]] (1998\u20132009)\n}}\n\nThe '''Grand Rapids Rampage''' were an [[arena football]] team based in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]]. The team began play in 1998 in the [[Arena Football League]] as an expansion team. They were last coached by [[Steve Thonn]]. Their home arena was the [[Van Andel Arena]].\n\n==History==\nThe team became the [[Detroit Drive]] in 1988 and, in 1994, became the [[Massachusetts Marauders]] for one season. Three years later, DP Fox Ventures, L.L.C. bought the team and moved it to Grand Rapids.\n\nThe team under its final name dates back to 1997. They began play as a professional team in 1998 in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], when [[Dan DeVos]] purchased the [[Massachusetts Marauders|Detroit Drive/Massachusetts Marauders]] franchise out of bankruptcy court. Grand Rapids was the smallest market in which the AFL had a franchise at the times of its disbanding. The Rampage played in the [[Van Andel Arena]], which is also the home of the [[American Hockey League|AHL]]'s [[Grand Rapids Griffins]]. They competed in the Central Division of the American Conference.\n\nThe Grand Rapids Rampage started play in 1998 under coach [[Michael Trigg]]. In 2001, with notable players [[Clint Dolezel]], and [[Terrill Shaw]], the Rampage went on to win their first [[ArenaBowl XV|ArenaBowl]]. This game was broadcast live on the [[ESPN on ABC|ABC Network]].\n\nThe Rampage's official mascot was a [[Rhinoceros]] named '''Blitz'''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |title=http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |access-date=2006-03-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050110073220/http://rampagefootball.com/community/mascot/ |archive-date=2005-01-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Rampage had a rivalry with the [[Nashville Kats]], one which dates back to the original Kats. This rivalry solidified with the Rampage's defeat of Nashville in [[ArenaBowl XV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/rampage-down-kats-in-arenabowl/n-2707556 |title=Rampage down Kats in Arenabowl |date=August 19, 2001 |publisher=OurSports Central |work=www.oursportscentral.com |accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Rampage also shared a rivalry with the [[Chicago Rush]], known as the Amtrak Classic, after the [[Amtrak]] railway system which connects the two cities. On July 6, 2008, the Amtrak Classic added an interesting chapter as the Rampage, losers of their last six meetings with Chicago, defeated their heavily favored opponents on the road. Grand Rapids entered the game as a 6 seed, and upended the #1 seeded Rush 58-41, in a game of controversial penalties and brawls.\n\nOn March 5, 2010, it was announced that the Rampage were officially out of business and had no plans to return.<ref>http://www.mlive.com/rampage/index.ssf/2010/03/rampage_dead_as_arena_football.html</ref>\n\n==Logo==\nThe Rampage's logo was a red [[rhinoceros]]. Its end zone is unique as being the only end zone that does not feature a team name or city. It simply says Arena Football in red with a black background.\n\n==Rampage highlights==\n* On Sunday, June 23, 2002, the Rampage hosted a game against the [[Georgia Force]]. After a low-scoring first quarter, the Rampage took a 28-15 halftime lead. However, the Force refused to go down, as they had a 41-35 lead with only 12 seconds left in the game. On one play, Quarterback [[Clint Dolezel]] threw a game-winning 31-yd touchdown pass to Offensive Specialist [[Steve Smith (wide receiver, born 1974)|Steve Smith]] (who hadn't played a down that game until the final play). The Rampage would win 42-41. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is ranked at #13.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29355&CLIP_FILE_ID=33336&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29355&CLIP_FILE_ID=33336&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* On Saturday, February 5, 2005, in a road game against their division-rival, the [[Colorado Crush]], Rampage quarterback [[Michael Bishop (football player)|Michael Bishop]] became the first Arena Football League player to run for 100 yards in a single game. It was only Bishop's third-ever start, yet he accomplished this feat on just six attempts. Despite falling 72-56, Bishop's helped set a bold new record. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is ranked at #12.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29664&CLIP_FILE_ID=33642&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=29664&CLIP_FILE_ID=33642&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* In a pregame warm-up, quarterback Michael Bishop threw a pass from one end zone, across the field, through the uprights and into the stands. On the AFL's 20 Greatest Highlights Countdown, this is tied at #9.<ref>[http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=30570&CLIP_FILE_ID=34585&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND http://www.arenafootball.com/mediaPlayer/video.dbml?DB_MENU_ID=&SPSID=38064&SPID=3172&DB_OEM_ID=3500&CLIP_ID=30570&CLIP_FILE_ID=34585&CONTENT_TYPE=ONDEMAND]</ref>\n* On Monday, March 24, 2008, The Rampage set the AFL record for the most points scored in a single game by a road team, beating the [[Kansas City Brigade]] 92-52. [[James MacPherson (American football)|James Macpherson]] went 24-27, nine touchdowns, and 307 yards in his first start for the Rampage. MacPherson would later go on to break the franchise record for touchdown passes in a later game.\n\n==Season-by-season==\n{{Main article|List of Grand Rapids Rampage seasons}}\n\n==Notable players==\n\n===Arena Football Hall of Famers===\n{| cla