{"title_page": "Vitus Bering (icebreaker)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=RUSMARKA-1854.jpg\n| Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=[[Russia]]\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Russia|government}}\n| Ship name=''Vitus Bering'' (''\u0412\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0433'')\n| Ship namesake=[[Vitus Bering]]\n| Ship owner=Dafne Line Shipping\n| Ship operator=[[Sovcomflot]]\n| Ship registry=*[[Limassol]], {{CYP}} (on delivery)<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n*2012\u2013: [[Saint Petersburg]], {{RUS}}<ref name=\"rs\" />\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=16 December 2010\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder=[[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]], [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| Ship original cost=$100 million\n| Ship yard number=506\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=19 January 2012\n| Ship launched=30 June 2012\n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed=21 December 2012<ref name=\"deliv2\">[http://arctech.fi/arctech-helsinki-shipyard-delivered-icebreaking-offshore-vessel/ Arctech Helsinki Shipyard Delivered Icebreaking Offshore Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 21 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n| Ship maiden voyage=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: UBGJ9<ref name=\"rs\" />\n*{{IMO Number|9613549}}\n*{{MMSI|209441000}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9613549|shipname=Vitus Bering|accessdate=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n| Ship fate=\n| Ship status=In service\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=<ref name=\"rs\">{{csr|register=RS|id=111097|shipname=Vitus Bering|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n| Ship class=\n| Ship type=[[Platform supply vessel]]\n| Ship tonnage=*{{GT|7,487}}\n*{{NetT|2,246}}\n*{{DWT|4,158}}\n| Ship displacement=\n| Ship length=*{{convert|99.9|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} ([[Length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|94.02|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Waterline length|waterline]])\n| Ship beam ={{convert|22.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height=\n| Ship draught={{convert|7.90|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft=\n| Ship depth={{convert|11.00|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship ice class=[[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|RMRS]] Icebreaker6\n| Ship power=*2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V32 (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}6,000{{nbsp}}kW)\n*2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 6L32 (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}3,000{{nbsp}}kW)\n| Ship propulsion=*Two [[ABB (company)|ABB]] [[Azipod]] VI1600 units (2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;6.5&nbsp;MW)\n*Two bow thrusters\n| Ship speed=*{{convert|15|kn}} (open water)\n*{{convert|3|kn}} in {{convert|1.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} level ice\n| Ship range=\n| Ship capacity=*700 m<sup>2</sup> cargo deck\n*195 evacuees\n| Ship endurance=30 days\n| Ship crew=Accommodation for 50\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Vitus Bering''''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0433}}) is a [[Russia]]n [[icebreaker|icebreaking]] [[platform supply vessel|platform supply]] and standby vessel owned by [[Sovcomflot]]. Built by [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]], she and her sister ship, [[Aleksey Chirikov (icebreaker)|''Aleksey Chirikov'']], were ordered on 16 December 2010, shortly after the joint venture agreement between [[STX Finland Cruise Oy]] and [[United Shipbuilding Corporation]] had been signed. Delivered to the owners on 21 December 2012, ''Vitus Bering'' will be used in the [[Arkutun-Dagi]] offshore oil field in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]].\n\n== Construction ==\n\n[[File:Vitus Bering at Arctech 2012-07-02.jpg|thumb|left|''Vitus Bering'' under construction at Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]]\n\nOnly six days after the agreement for the formation of the company was signed between STX Finland Cruise Oy and United Shipbuilding Corporation on 10 December 2010, the newly founded Arctech Helsinki Shipyard received an order for two multipurpose icebreaking supply vessels from the Russian state-owned shipping company Sovcomflot. The value of the shipbuilding contract was US$200 million and the construction of the vessels would provide work for 1,000 [[man-year]]s.<ref name=\"arctechmustamaki\">[http://arctech.fi/news/ Esko Mustam\u00e4ki appointed as the Managing Director of Arctech Helsinki Shipyard Inc.] Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 4 April 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref> Initially, the ships were to be delivered to the customer together in April 2013,<ref name=\"arctechorder\">[http://arctech.fi/news/ Arctech receives an order for two new icebreaking Supply Vessels from Sovcomflot]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 16 December 2010.</ref> after which they would be used for standby, supply and [[ice management]] of ''Berkut'', an offshore platform operated by [[Exxon Neftegas|Exxon Neftegas Limited]] in the Arkutun-Dagi offshore oil field in the Sea of Okhotsk.<ref name=\"arkutundagi\">{{cite web |url=http://www.offshoreenergytoday.com/russia-sovcomflot-successful-in-exxon-neftegas-supply-vessel-tender/ |title=Russia: Sovcomflot Successiful in Exxon Neftegas Supply Vessel Tender |publisher=Offshore Energy Today |date=2010-12-20 |accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the ship was assembled at Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, the majority of the steel blocks were manufactured by the Russian [[Vyborg Shipyard]] as the [[Hietalahti shipyard]] no longer has such production capacity. Only five of the 42 hull blocks for the two vessels were manufactured locally in Helsinki to ramp up the production while the remaining blocks were produced and partially outfitted in [[Vyborg]] and then brought to Helsinki on a barge for final outfitting, painting and hull assembly.<ref name=\"arctechstarts\">[http://arctech.fi/arctech-started-the-hull-assembly-of-multifunctional-icebreaking-supply-vessel/ Arctech Started the Hull Assembly of Multifunctional Icebreaking Supply Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 19 January 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> The steel-cutting ceremony for the first vessel was held at Vyborg Shipyard on 6 July 2011 and production began in Helsinki in August 2011.<ref name=\"arctechblocksstart\">[http://www.arctech.fi/news Construction of multi-purpose icebreaking service vessel begins]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 6 July 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref>\n\nThe keel laying ceremony of the first vessel was held on 19 January 2012 when the first block, a 353-ton midship section manufactured in Helsinki, was lowered to the shipyard's covered drydock.<ref name=\"arctechstarts\" /> ''Vitus Bering'' was launched and floated out on 30 June 2012. The hull assembly of the second vessel began in July and she was launched on 23 November 2012, one day after the first vessel left for one week [[sea trial]]s.<ref>[http://arctech.fi/launch-of-arctic-offshore-vessel-at-arctech/ Launch of Arctic Offshore Vessel at Arctech]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 30 June 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref><ref>[http://arctech.fi/arctech-launched-sister-of-arctic-offshore-vessel/ Arctech Launched Sister of Arctic Offshore Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 23 November 2012. {{retrieved| accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref><ref>[http://arctech.fi/arctic-offshore-vessel-vitus-bering-on-sea-trial-2/ Arctic offshore vessel Vitus Bering on sea trial]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 22 November 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref> ''Vitus Bering'' was delivered to Sovcomflot on 21 December 2012, four months ahead of the original schedule.<ref name=\"deliv2\" /><ref name=\"deliv\">[http://arctech.fi/arctic-offshore-vessel-will-be-delivered-from-arctech-4-months-in-advance/ Arctic Offshore Vessel Will Be Delivered from Arctech 4 months in Advance]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 15 August 2012. {{retrieved |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> From Helsinki, she headed for [[St. Petersburg]], where the new vessel was visited by president [[Vladimir Putin]] on 10 January 2013.<ref>[http://maritime-connector.com/news/general/as-offshore-oil-prospects-expand-putin-calls-for-more-high-tech-ships/ As Offshore Oil Prospects Expand, Putin Calls for More High-Tech Ships]. Maritime Connector, 12 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\nThe ship is named after the [[Denmark|Danish]] explorer [[Vitus Bering]] who, while in Russian service, became the first European to [[Great Northern Expedition|discover Alaska]].<ref name=\"scf\">[http://www.scf-group.com/npage.aspx?anim=1&cs=4&cs2=1&cid=3&parm=@id=304&templ=vessel Vitus Bering]. SCF Group. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Technical details ==\n\n''Vitus Bering'' is an upgraded version of ''[[SCF Sakhalin]]'', a similar icebreaking platform supply vessel built at Helsinki in 2005.<ref name=\"arctech_scfsakhalin\">[http://arctech.fi/ships/scf-sakhalin/ SCF Sakhalin]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref> Several modifications have been made to the original design, including adding a fourth main engine, but the hull form is nearly identical. The most noticeable external difference is the covered foredeck, which will protect the mooring equipment from icing.\n\n''Vitus Bering'' is {{convert|99.9|m|ft}} [[length overall|long overall]]. Her hull has a moulded breadth of {{convert|22.1|m|ft}} and depth of {{convert|11.00|m|ft}} to upper deck. When loaded to a draught of {{convert|7.90|m|ft}}, the [[deadweight tonnage]] of the ship is 4,158 tons. The four [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]]<ref name=\"hs20120814\">[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Helsinki+yard+turns+to+special+vessels+for+Arctic+conditions+/1329104614839 Helsinki yard turns to special vessels for Arctic conditions]. Helsingin Sanomat, 14 August 2012.</ref> diesel generating sets \u2014 two [[V12 engine|twelve-cylinder]] 12V32 and two [[straight-six engine|six-cylinder]] 6L32 engines \u2014 have a combined output of {{convert|18,000|kW|hp|abbr=on}} and provide power for all shipboard consumers, including two 6.5 MW [[ABB Group|ABB]] [[Azipod]] VI1600 propulsion units.<ref name=\"abb_reflist\">[https://library.e.abb.com/public/98a7ddd74d7ecb3bc1257b09004c14ab/ABB%20Propulsion%20Products%20reference%20list%202013.pdf References - Propulsion Products]. ABB. {{retrieved|accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref><ref name=\"arctech_pruju\">[http://arctech.fi/wp-content/uploads/NB506_brochure.pdf Multifunctional icebreaking supply vessel (MIBSV)]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> A [[double acting ship]], ''Vitus Bering'' is designed to be able to break ice both ahead and astern. She is capable of operating in ice up to {{convert|1.7|m|ft}} thick and maintain a speed of {{convert|3|kn}} in level ice with a thickness of {{convert|1.5|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"motorship\">[http://www.motorship.com/news101/russian-multi-purpose-icebreaking-psv-begins-build-in-finland Russian multi-purpose icebreaking PSV begins build in Finland] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130129021500/http://www.motorship.com/news101/russian-multi-purpose-icebreaking-psv-begins-build-in-finland |date=2013-01-29 }}. The Motor Ship, 20 January 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> Her ice class, assigned by the [[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping]], is ''Icebreaker6''.<ref name=\"rs\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9613549|''Vitus Bering''}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=RUSMARKA-1854.jpg\n| Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=[[Russia]]\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Russia|government}}\n| Ship name=''Vitus Bering'' (''\u0412\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0433'')\n| Ship namesake=[[Vitus Bering]]\n| Ship owner=Dafne Line Shipping\n| Ship operator=[[Sovcomflot]]\n| Ship registry=*[[Limassol]], {{CYP}} (on delivery)<ref name=\"equasis\" />\n*2012\u2013: [[Saint Petersburg]], {{RUS}}<ref name=\"rs\" />\n| Ship route=\n| Ship ordered=16 December 2010\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder=[[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]], [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| Ship original cost=$100 million\n| Ship yard number=506\n| Ship way number=\n| Ship laid down=19 January 2012\n| Ship launched=30 June 2012\n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed=21 December 2012<ref name=\"deliv2\">[http://arctech.fi/arctech-helsinki-shipyard-delivered-icebreaking-offshore-vessel/ Arctech Helsinki Shipyard Delivered Icebreaking Offshore Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 21 December 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n| Ship maiden voyage=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship identification=*[[Maritime call sign|Call sign]]: UBGJ9<ref name=\"rs\" />\n*{{IMO Number|9613549}}\n*{{MMSI|209441000}}<ref name=\"equasis\">{{csr|register=E|id=9613549|shipname=Vitus Bering|accessdate=2012-01-07}}</ref>\n| Ship fate=\n| Ship status=In service\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=<ref name=\"rs\">{{csr|register=RS|id=111097|shipname=Vitus Bering|accessdate=2013-01-01}}</ref>\n| Ship class=\n| Ship type=[[Platform supply vessel]]\n| Ship tonnage=*{{GT|7,487}}\n*{{NetT|2,246}}\n*{{DWT|4,158}}\n| Ship displacement=\n| Ship length=*{{convert|99.9|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} ([[Length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|94.02|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Waterline length|waterline]])\n| Ship beam ={{convert|22.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| Ship height=\n| Ship draught={{convert|7.90|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft=\n| Ship depth={{convert|11.00|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship ice class=[[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping|RMRS]] Icebreaker6\n| Ship power=*2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 12V32 (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}6,000{{nbsp}}kW)\n*2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}[[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]] 6L32 (2{{nbsp}}&times;{{nbsp}}3,000{{nbsp}}kW)\n| Ship propulsion=*Two [[ABB (company)|ABB]] [[Azipod]] VI1600 units (2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;6.5&nbsp;MW)\n*Two bow thrusters\n| Ship speed=*{{convert|15|kn}} (open water)\n*{{convert|3|kn}} in {{convert|1.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} level ice\n| Ship range=\n| Ship capacity=*700 m<sup>2</sup> cargo deck\n*195 evacuees\n| Ship endurance=30 days\n| Ship crew=Accommodation for 50\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Vitus Bering''''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0441 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0433}}) is a [[Russia]]n [[icebreaker|icebreaking]] [[platform supply vessel|platform supply]] and standby vessel owned by [[Sovcomflot]]. Built by [[Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]] in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]], she and her sister ship, [[Aleksey Chirikov (icebreaker)|''Aleksey Chirikov'']], were ordered on 16 December 2010, shortly after the joint venture agreement between [[STX Finland Cruise Oy]] and [[United Shipbuilding Corporation]] had been signed. Delivered to the owners on 21 December 2012, ''Vitus Bering'' will be used in the [[Arkutun-Dagi]] offshore oil field in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]].\n\n== Construction ==\n\n[[File:Vitus Bering at Arctech 2012-07-02.jpg|thumb|left|''Vitus Bering'' under construction at Arctech Helsinki Shipyard]]\n\nOnly six days after the agreement for the formation of the company was signed between STX Finland Cruise Oy and United Shipbuilding Corporation on 10 December 2010, the newly founded Arctech Helsinki Shipyard received an order for two multipurpose icebreaking supply vessels from the Russian state-owned shipping company Sovcomflot. The value of the shipbuilding contract was US$200 million and the construction of the vessels would provide work for 1,000 [[man-year]]s.<ref name=\"arctechmustamaki\">[http://arctech.fi/news/ Esko Mustam\u00e4ki appointed as the Managing Director of Arctech Helsinki Shipyard Inc.] Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 4 April 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref> Initially, the ships were to be delivered to the customer together in April 2013,<ref name=\"arctechorder\">[http://arctech.fi/news/ Arctech receives an order for two new icebreaking Supply Vessels from Sovcomflot]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 16 December 2010.</ref> after which they would be used for standby, supply and [[ice management]] of ''Berkut'', an offshore platform operated by [[Exxon Neftegas|Exxon Neftegas Limited]] in the Arkutun-Dagi offshore oil field in the Sea of Okhotsk.<ref name=\"arkutundagi\">{{cite web |url=http://www.offshoreenergytoday.com/russia-sovcomflot-successful-in-exxon-neftegas-supply-vessel-tender/ |title=Russia: Sovcomflot Successiful in Exxon Neftegas Supply Vessel Tender |publisher=Offshore Energy Today |date=2010-12-20 |accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the ship was assembled at Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, the majority of the steel blocks were manufactured by the Russian [[Vyborg Shipyard]] as the [[Hietalahti shipyard]] no longer has such production capacity. Only five of the 42 hull blocks for the two vessels were manufactured locally in Helsinki to ramp up the production while the remaining blocks were produced and partially outfitted in [[Vyborg]] and then brought to Helsinki on a barge for final outfitting, painting and hull assembly.<ref name=\"arctechstarts\">[http://arctech.fi/arctech-started-the-hull-assembly-of-multifunctional-icebreaking-supply-vessel/ Arctech Started the Hull Assembly of Multifunctional Icebreaking Supply Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 19 January 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> The steel-cutting ceremony for the first vessel was held at Vyborg Shipyard on 6 July 2011 and production began in Helsinki in August 2011.<ref name=\"arctechblocksstart\">[http://www.arctech.fi/news Construction of multi-purpose icebreaking service vessel begins]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 6 July 2011. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref>\n\nThe keel laying ceremony of the first vessel was held on 19 January 2012 when the first block, a 353-ton midship section manufactured in Helsinki, was lowered to the shipyard's covered drydock.<ref name=\"arctechstarts\" /> ''Vitus Bering'' was launched and floated out on 30 June 2012. The hull assembly of the second vessel began in July and she was launched on 23 November 2012, one day after the first vessel left for one week [[sea trial]]s.<ref>[http://arctech.fi/launch-of-arctic-offshore-vessel-at-arctech/ Launch of Arctic Offshore Vessel at Arctech]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 30 June 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref><ref>[http://arctech.fi/arctech-launched-sister-of-arctic-offshore-vessel/ Arctech Launched Sister of Arctic Offshore Vessel]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 23 November 2012. {{retrieved| accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref><ref>[http://arctech.fi/arctic-offshore-vessel-vitus-bering-on-sea-trial-2/ Arctic offshore vessel Vitus Bering on sea trial]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 22 November 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref> ''Vitus Bering'' was delivered to Sovcomflot on 21 December 2012, four months ahead of the original schedule.<ref name=\"deliv2\" /><ref name=\"deliv\">[http://arctech.fi/arctic-offshore-vessel-will-be-delivered-from-arctech-4-months-in-advance/ Arctic Offshore Vessel Will Be Delivered from Arctech 4 months in Advance]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard, 15 August 2012. {{retrieved |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> From Helsinki, she headed for [[St. Petersburg]], where the new vessel was visited by president [[Vladimir Putin]] on 10 January 2013.<ref>[http://maritime-connector.com/news/general/as-offshore-oil-prospects-expand-putin-calls-for-more-high-tech-ships/ As Offshore Oil Prospects Expand, Putin Calls for More High-Tech Ships]. Maritime Connector, 12 January 2013. {{retrieved|accessdate=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\nThe ship is named after the [[Denmark|Danish]] explorer [[Vitus Bering]] who, while in Russian service, became the first European to [[Great Northern Expedition|discover Alaska]].<ref name=\"scf\">[http://www.scf-group.com/npage.aspx?anim=1&cs=4&cs2=1&cid=3&parm=@id=304&templ=vessel Vitus Bering]. SCF Group. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref>\n\n== Technical details ==\n\n''Vitus Bering'' is an upgraded version of ''[[SCF Sakhalin]]'', a similar icebreaking platform supply vessel built at Helsinki in 2005.<ref name=\"arctech_scfsakhalin\">[http://arctech.fi/ships/scf-sakhalin/ SCF Sakhalin]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-28}}</ref> Several modifications have been made to the original design, including adding a fourth main engine, but the hull form is nearly identical. The most noticeable external difference is the covered foredeck, which will protect the mooring equipment from icing.\n\n''Vitus Bering'' is {{convert|99.9|m|ft}} [[length overall|long overall]]. Her hull has a moulded breadth of {{convert|22.1|m|ft}} and depth of {{convert|11.00|m|ft}} to upper deck. When loaded to a draught of {{convert|7.90|m|ft}}, the [[deadweight tonnage]] of the ship is 4,158 tons. The four [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]]<ref name=\"hs20120814\">[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Helsinki+yard+turns+to+special+vessels+for+Arctic+conditions+/1329104614839 Helsinki yard turns to special vessels for Arctic conditions]. Helsingin Sanomat, 14 August 2012.</ref> diesel generating sets \u2014 two [[V12 engine|twelve-cylinder]] 12V32 and two [[straight-six engine|six-cylinder]] 6L32 engines \u2014 have a combined output of {{convert|18,000|kW|hp|abbr=on}} and provide power for all shipboard consumers, including two 6.5 MW [[ABB Group|ABB]] [[Azipod]] VI1600 propulsion units.<ref name=\"abb_reflist\">[https://library.e.abb.com/public/98a7ddd74d7ecb3bc1257b09004c14ab/ABB%20Propulsion%20Products%20reference%20list%202013.pdf References - Propulsion Products]. ABB. {{retrieved|accessdate=2015-05-28}}</ref><ref name=\"arctech_pruju\">[http://arctech.fi/wp-content/uploads/NB506_brochure.pdf Multifunctional icebreaking supply vessel (MIBSV)]. Arctech Helsinki Shipyard. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> A [[double acting ship]], ''Vitus Bering'' is designed to be able to break ice both ahead and astern. She is capable of operating in ice up to {{convert|1.7|m|ft}} thick and maintain a speed of {{convert|3|kn}} in level ice with a thickness of {{convert|1.5|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"motorship\">[http://www.motorship.com/news101/russian-multi-purpose-icebreaking-psv-begins-build-in-finland Russian multi-purpose icebreaking PSV begins build in Finland] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130129021500/http://www.motorship.com/news101/russian-multi-purpose-icebreaking-psv-begins-build-in-finland |date=2013-01-29 }}. The Motor Ship, 20 January 2012. {{retrieved | accessdate=2012-01-27}}</ref> Her ice class, assigned by the [[Russian Maritime Register of Shipping]], is ''Icebreaker6''.<ref name=\"rs\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:2012 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitus_Bering_(icebreaker)"}
